issue.title: Excessive DEBUG logging for networked entity updates causes massive log spam
issue.body:
### Issue description

The mod generates an extreme amount of DEBUG-level logs for machine network updates, flooding `debug.log` with repetitive messages like:  

```plaintext
[Server thread/DEBUG] [oritech/]: sending networked entity update: TICK at BlockPos{x=4008, y=72, z=-56} for oritech:refinery_entity
[Server thread/DEBUG] [oritech/]: sending networked entity update: SPARSE_TICK at BlockPos{x=4040, y=72, z=-40} for oritech:foundry_entity
```

**Impact:**  
- Log files grow **100MB+ in just a few hours** with only a few machines running  
- Makes server debugging difficult due to log bloat  
- Wastes disk I/O and may affect performance  
- Impossible to share logs for troubleshooting  


Would appreciate any fix or config option to control this logging behavior. Thanks! 

### Steps to reproduce

1. Place a few Oritech machines (e.g., Refinery, Foundry)  
2. Run them for a short time (~1 hour)  
3. Check `logs/debug.log` â€“ it will be filled with these messages  

### Minecraft version

1.21.1 (Latest)

### Platform

Neoforge

### Loader version

21.1.193

### Oritech version

0.17.3

### Other relevant versions

_No response_

### If a (crash)log is relevant for this issue, link it here: (It's almost always relevant)

_No response_

milestone.title: Login/ Signup/ Authentication
milestone.description: Screens and components relating to the initial stage of the user journey of the MVP.

issue.body:
Why

As a new or returning cherry user
I want to sign in with Google, Apple (iOS), Email/Password, or Facebook
So that I can securely access my account across devices

Acceptance Criteria...

Google Sign-In
	â€¢	SCENARIO: First-time Google sign-in (success)
	â€¢	Given the app is installed and the user taps â€œContinue with Googleâ€
	â€¢	When Google OAuth completes successfully
	â€¢	Then the user is signed in and lands on the post-login screen with their profile created
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Google sign-in canceled
	â€¢	Given the user has opened the Google auth sheet
	â€¢	When the user cancels or closes the sheet
	â€¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a non-blocking â€œSign in canceledâ€ message
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Google sign-in error
	â€¢	Given the device has poor connectivity or OAuth fails
	â€¢	When the flow errors
	â€¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a generic error with a â€œTry againâ€ option
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Existing Google user
	â€¢	Given the email already exists in our auth provider
	â€¢	When the user signs in with the same Google account
	â€¢	Then their existing profile is loaded and session starts (no duplicate profile)
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Analytics/telemetry
	â€¢	Given any Google auth attempt
	â€¢	When success, cancel, or error occurs
	â€¢	Then an event is logged with outcome and error code (if any)

Sign in with Apple (iOS)
	â€¢	SCENARIO: First-time Apple sign-in (success)
	â€¢	Given the user taps â€œContinue with Appleâ€ on iOS
	â€¢	When Apple Sign In completes successfully (real email or Private Relay)
	â€¢	Then the user is signed in and lands on post-login screen with profile created
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Apple sign-in canceled
	â€¢	Given the Apple sign-in sheet is visible
	â€¢	When the user cancels
	â€¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a non-blocking message
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Apple sign-in error
	â€¢	Given a network or credential error
	â€¢	When the flow errors
	â€¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a retry option
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Email relay stability
	â€¢	Given the user uses â€œHide My Emailâ€
	â€¢	When they return on the same device or another iOS device
	â€¢	Then they can sign in again and reach the same account
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Analytics/telemetry
	â€¢	Log success/cancel/error with Apple-specific reason codes where available

Email & Password
	â€¢	SCENARIO: New account â€” email verification
	â€¢	Given the user enters a valid email and strong password
	â€¢	When they tap â€œCreate accountâ€
	â€¢	Then a verification email is sent and the UI shows â€œCheck your emailâ€ state
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Email verification complete
	â€¢	Given the user clicks the verification link
	â€¢	When they return to the app
	â€¢	Then they can sign in and reach the post-login screen
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Weak or invalid password
	â€¢	Given the user enters a weak or invalid password
	â€¢	When they attempt to create the account
	â€¢	Then inline validation explains the issue and prevents submission
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Existing email
	â€¢	Given the email is already registered
	â€¢	When the user attempts to sign up
	â€¢	Then theyâ€™re prompted to â€œSign inâ€ instead (no duplicate account)
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Password reset
	â€¢	Given the user taps â€œForgot password?â€
	â€¢	When they submit a registered email
	â€¢	Then a reset email is sent and the UI confirms â€œReset link sentâ€
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Email sign-in error handling
	â€¢	Given network or invalid-credentials errors
	â€¢	When the user tries to sign in
	â€¢	Then descriptive, non-sensitive error feedback is shown and can retry
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Analytics/telemetry
	â€¢	Log create, verify sent, verify complete, sign-in success, sign-in failure, reset sent

Facebook Login
	â€¢	SCENARIO: First-time Facebook sign-in (success)
	â€¢	Given the user taps â€œContinue with Facebookâ€
	â€¢	When Facebook OAuth completes successfully
	â€¢	Then the user is signed in and lands on post-login screen with profile created
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Facebook sign-in canceled
	â€¢	Given the Facebook sheet is presented
	â€¢	When the user cancels
	â€¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a non-blocking message
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Facebook sign-in error
	â€¢	Given a network or provider error
	â€¢	When the flow errors
	â€¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a retry option
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Existing Facebook user
	â€¢	Given the email already exists
	â€¢	When the user signs in with Facebook
	â€¢	Then the same account is used (no duplicate), or the user is guided to link accounts if provider conflict occurs
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Analytics/telemetry
	â€¢	Log success/cancel/error with provider error codes

Cross-cutting (All Providers)
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Session persistence
	â€¢	Given the user successfully signs in
	â€¢	When they relaunch the app within the session TTL
	â€¢	Then they remain signed in without re-authenticating
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Sign out
	â€¢	Given the user is signed in
	â€¢	When they tap â€œSign outâ€
	â€¢	Then session is cleared and they return to the pre-login screen
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Rate limiting / lockout UX
	â€¢	Given repeated failed attempts (e.g., >N within M minutes)
	â€¢	When throttling/lockout happens
	â€¢	Then the user sees a friendly throttle message and next-steps timing
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Accessibility
	â€¢	Given the auth screen
	â€¢	When using VoiceOver and large text
	â€¢	Then all buttons/labels are accessible and readable
	â€¢	SCENARIO: Privacy & copy
	â€¢	Given any auth screen
	â€¢	When displayed
	â€¢	Then Terms & Privacy links are present and open successfully in-app

Proposed Implementation
	â€¢	Auth provider: Use your existing auth backend (e.g., Firebase Authentication) with providers enabled for Google, Apple (iOS), Email/Password, and Facebook.
	â€¢	Mobile SDKs:
	â€¢	Google: platform-specific Google Sign-In SDK or Firebase Auth Google provider
	â€¢	Apple (iOS): Sign in with Apple framework with nonce to prevent replay; require â€œEmailâ€ scope
	â€¢	Email/Password: built-in provider; enable email verification templates
	â€¢	Facebook: Facebook Login SDK or Firebase Auth Facebook provider
	â€¢	Environment/config:
	â€¢	Store OAuth client IDs, Apple team/service IDs, and FB App ID in secure env (per build scheme).
	â€¢	Configure URL types/redirect URIs for each provider.
	â€¢	Linking accounts:
	â€¢	Implement provider collision handling; offer â€œLink accountsâ€ path when email exists with different provider.
	â€¢	Emulator/Mocking (MVP):
	â€¢	Use auth emulator or a mock auth layer to simulate success, cancel, and error states per provider.
	â€¢	Stub network failures to validate error UI.
	â€¢	Log test outcomes to a QA collection for audit.
	â€¢	Analytics:
	â€¢	Emit events: auth_attempt, auth_success, auth_cancel, auth_error, email_verify_sent, email_verify_complete, password_reset_sent.
	â€¢	Include provider, error_code, and latency_ms.
	â€¢	Test data:
	â€¢	Create test accounts: google âœ”, apple (relay) âœ”, email_verified âœ”/âœ–, facebook âœ”.
	â€¢	QA checklist (manual):
	â€¢	Buttons visible: Google, Apple (iOS), Email, Facebook
	â€¢	Success, cancel, error flows validated for each provider
	â€¢	Email verification and password reset flows validated
	â€¢	Session persists across relaunch; sign-out clears state
	â€¢	Accessibility: VoiceOver labels, Dynamic Type, contrast
	â€¢	Terms/Privacy links function

Merge pull request #26 from mahadi-zulfiker/mainpage

Mainpage

Increase frameworks dependency version to 6.16

de97275a387abcbca6fcb185bcbd1b69c30f5c66 here in NeoChat depends on
de05764b4764d5641c647bb75bdf184522f63989 in Kirigami. However, that
Kirigami commit only landed in Frameworks 6.16, while the minimum
Frameworks version specified here in NeoChat's CMake remained at 6.12.

Because the CMake dependency version wasn't set to 6.16, a potential
build-time error was converted into a potential runtime error. And
that's exactly what happened for NeoChat's 25.08 Flatpak packaging,
because the KDE Runtime doesn't yet have Frameworks 6.16 in it.

issue.body:
@Jimmyzmac Thank you for reaching out. Please note that this repository is a blockchain explorer and does not have the capability to manage or process transactions. As such, weâ€™ve marked this issue as resolved on our end.

For help with transactions or transfer issues, we recommend contacting our support team directly at interact.gitdapps@gmail.com. Theyâ€™ll be happy to assist you further.

â¸»

User Description of Issue:
When connecting to drift.trade through brave mobile Android browser, normally when you connect your wallet brave wallet is listed as an option but for some reason there is no detection of that wallet as of the last couple of mornings where it was present all the time over the last several months. We didn't even update our browser or any apps but just one morning the option for brave wallet was not there. this only happens b&su on the mobile brave wallet whereas the desktop is fine. I attempted to try another decks such as jup.ag, the wallet is detected no problem but with drift somehow I believe the code has been altered or some sort of glitch is in the code to prevent brave mobile wallet from being detected. Has been a recently discussed issue amongst many others and I'm wondering if people in this community have also experienced the same problem and if there is a solution or if anyone from drift is reading this message to submit this as a bug?

issue.title: Add cost tracking when using bedrock passthrough
issue.body:
Hi, we are running Litellm with bedrock as the backend, its working great for chat.
We tried using claude-code with litellm as the llm backend (https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code/bedrock-vertex-proxies#litellm), without success, until we set litellm to passthrough, but then we dont have cost tracking per user, which is required for us as part of this solution.
Thanks in advance for the help.

comment.body:
hey @archananarayanan, did you manage to run the bedrock passthrough without creating aliases? @krrishdholakia, please see the steps below to reproduce the issue:

I have a config like this:
```
...
  - model_name: bedrock-us.anthropic.claude-sonnet-4-20250514-v1:0
    litellm_params:
      model: bedrock/us.anthropic.claude-sonnet-4-20250514-v1:0
      num_retries: 3
...
```

When I specify the bedrock model name directly, I get an error from LiteLLM:
```
curl --location 'https://internal-ai-gateway.ancestryl3.int/bedrock/model/us.amazon.nova-pro-v1:0/invoke' ...
```
Response:
```
{
    "error": {
        "message": "{'error': 'allm_passthrough_route: Invalid model name passed in model=us.amazon.nova-pro-v1:0. Call `/v1/models` to view available models for your key.'}",
        "type": "None",
        "param": "None",
        "code": "400"
    }
}
```
If I set the LiteLLM model name, then I get an error from AWS Bedrock itself.
```
curl --location 'https://internal-ai-gateway.ancestryl3.int/bedrock/model/bedrock-us.amazon.nova-pro-v1:0/invoke' ...
```
Response:
```
{
    "error": {
        "message": "{\"message\":\"The provided model identifier is invalid.\"}. Received Model Group=bedrock-us.amazon.nova-pro-v1:0\nAvailable Model Group Fallbacks=None",
        "type": "None",
        "param": "None",
        "code": "500"
    }
}
```

LiteLLM version: 1.74.3.

commits.message:
Create Generating truth_vcf

Generating a truth VCF is necessary because it provides a high-confidence set of genotypes to benchmark imputation accuracy. Without this ground truth, it would be impossible to measure how well imputed calls match real genetic variation, especially across coverage levels, allele frequencies, and filtering thresholds.
